        <link:link rdf:resource="#item_1359"/>
        <dc:title>Single-Beacon Localization for Mobile Robot: A Set Membership Filtering Approach</dc:title>
        <dcterms:abstract>In this letter, we study the localization problem of a mobile robot with range measurement from a single beacon. Previous ﬁltering-based studies usually required accurate statistics of noises to be theoretically sound and reliable, which is diﬃcult to obtain in practical systems. To solve this problem, we propose an accurate and eﬃcient localization method based on a set-membership ﬁltering framework with constrained zonotopes. This method includes three novel steps. First, we design a convex optimization relaxation method to handle the non-convexity caused by the single-beacon range measurement. Then, a halfspace-intersection reﬁnement is proposed which improves the estimation accuracy. Finally, we provide a sliding-window recursive method that simultaneously guarantees the accuracy and the eﬃciency. Simulations and ﬁeld experiments corroborate the eﬀectiveness of our proposed method. © 2024 IEEE. Personal use is permitted, but republication/redistribution requires IEEE permission. Number of references: 30 Main heading: Random processes Controlled terms: Convex optimization - Mobile robots - Stochastic systems Uncontrolled terms: Beacon localization - Constrained zonotope - Localization for mobile robot - Location awareness - Noise - Noise measurements - Range measurements - Set membership ﬁltering - Single-beacon localization Zonotopes Classiﬁcation code: 731.1 Control Systems - 731.5 Robotics - 922.1 Probability Theory - 961 Systems Science DOI: 10.1109/LRA.2024.3406190 Funding Details: Number: U23B2032,U2241214, Acronym: NSFC, Sponsor: National Natural Science Foundation of China; Number: -, Acronym: NSFC, Sponsor: National Natural Science Foundation of China; Funding text: This letter was recommended for publication by Associate Editor Y. Wang and Editor S. Behnke upon evaluation of the reviewers comments. This work was supported by National Natural Science Foundation of China under Grant U23B2032 and Grant U2241214. Compendex references: YES Database: Compendex Data Provider: Engineering Village Compilation and indexing terms, Copyright 2025 Elsevier Inc.</dcterms:abstract>
        <dc:date>11/2024</dc:date>
        <z:language>en</z:language>
        <z:shortTitle>Single-Beacon Localization for Mobile Robot</z:shortTitle>
        <z:libraryCatalog>DOI.org (Crossref)</z:libraryCatalog>
